  "prompt": "Do anti-money laundering regulations exist?",
  "response": "Yes, anti-money laundering (AML) regulations exist in many countries around the world. These regulations are designed to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income. Key aspects include:\n\n1. In the United States:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- Requires financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n\n2. Internationally:\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) sets global standards\n- Most developed countries have AML laws\n- Regulations cover banks, financial services, cryptocurrencies, and other sectors\n\n3. Common requirements:\n- Customer identification\n- Transaction monitoring\n- Reporting large or suspicious transactions\n- Maintaining records\n- Implementing compliance programs\n\n4. Penalties for non-compliance can include:\n- Significant fines\n- Criminal charges\n- Loss of business licenses\n\nThese regulations aim to combat financial crimes like money laundering, terrorist financing, and other illegal financial activities.",
